As an introverted creative individual who is self-employed and very privacy-conscious, running a business shouldn't feel so awkward, but sometimes it does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to deal with large (evil) tech companies in an extroverted way. Advertise here, follow the algorithms, share your charm. Get verified on that service, stay online all day, answer questions with your own videos, and respond immediately. Videos, videos, and more videos.
1/3
This year is a year of transformation for me.
I don't want to continue dedicating my money, data, and energy to large tech companies, nor do I want to listen to mentors who only apply a single extroverted solution to everyone. I am exploring new business models while also trying to overcome my long-held belief that only by doing things in a certain specific way can one succeed.
Good luck to me!
The first step has been taken.
I have left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and logged out of my personal WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed the last external tracker from my website - Google Analytics, and it felt great.
To better support GDPR, I recently subscribed to a European CRM service and will be migrating my business there over the next few weeks.
I have transferred my MX records to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for basic email verification anymore.
3/3
